Clearly not. The creature merely hissed and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Luckily, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she almost lost her grip on its too smooth scales.
"HOW DO YOU KILL THEM?," Nyssi shouted.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD!"
"THIS ISN'T GOING TO BE EASY!"
Thassalin exhaled, then circled around to approach the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed him, somewhat startled when a bolt of fire struck it from behind. The creature had not noticed that it was no longer alone. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then violently struck its head with his tail, causing it to veer off course.
Growling and hissing, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking in the light from the sky and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but he brushed against the tops of the trees before crashing into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged directly at him, dragging the dark cloud in its wake.
"Kayel!," exclaimed Tenuk as he emerged from the cloud and began flying in circles to try to spot Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What do we do, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to get up. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, almost unnatural healing powers had already started to take effect. The same could not be said of Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try to reach Thassalin, but she could not see more than two meters ahead of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by the impious shadows. And within those shadows, something was screaming.
An horrible, club-like tail came down beside Nyssi, knocking her over. She noticed, however, that the tail was swaying, not aiming at her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and scratching the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster and disorienting it.
A gunshot suddenly rang out, and the monster collapsed silently, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, gun in hand and breathing heavily.
"This... is the weirdest shadow leap I've ever done... Thanto kat'olon...", gasped Kayel. His eyes glowed with a dark light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow color.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel had strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, because most people considered them impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed quite surprised himself.
"Are you okay?", Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm okay. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, as Tenuk made his way to land beside him, returning to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the drool continued to stick to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what this thing was, something howled and lunged from a nearby bush. However, the beast didn't have time to reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Taking no risks, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature instantly.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily turning off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you all right?"
"You practically missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all abandoned me. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can someone tell me what these disgusting things are?"
Retvik's question fortunately received an answer from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut up and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible monster god that we... helped kill?" Tenuk stammered.
"YES. EXACTLY. THERE MIGHT BE MORE, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO AIM FOR THEIR HEADS. I'M MISSING A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE ISN'T FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin approached Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS CAPABLE OF KILLING UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thank you... I guess," Kayel said with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then grabbed her camera to photograph the beasts, now truly dead. She then took out her favorite dagger, the one of the god of death, and began cutting one of the creature's horns, then moved on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures caught fire and quickly turned into piles of ash. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut.
"Well... that's both convenient and not convenient at all," she sighed. "At least I still have the photos..."
